\date{\today}

\begin{abstract}
In this paper we examine the ultrafast optical response of the crystalline and amorphous phases of the phase change material Ge$_2$Sb$_2$Te$_5$. By simultaneously recording the changes in the transmissivity and reflectivity of thin film samples, we obtain the time-dependent evolution of the dielectric function for the two phases. By analyzing the response, we can obtain both structural and electronic information. We find that, for fluences up to 50\% of the single shot transformation fluence, the structural potential remains unperturbed and no bond softening occurs. The change in optical properties in both phases is dictated by the photoexcited electrons; however their behavior is different. In the amorphous phase the photoexcited electrons respond as a free electron gas in a semiconductor, whereas the photoexcited electrons in the cyrstalline phase block resonant-bonding transitions. 
\end{abstract}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}
Phase change materials (PCMs) based on alloys of Ge, Sb and Te can be easily, rapidly, and reversibly switched between ordered-crystalline and disordered-amorphous crystallographic arrangements. Switching between states is typically achieved by a heat-quench cycle, which can be laser-~\cite{Weidenhof2001, Liu2012b} or current-induced~\cite{Lankhorst2005a, Loke2012b}. Amorphization is achieved by heating the crystalline phase above the melting point followed by rapid cooling. Re-crystallization is achieved by heating above the glass transition temperature and then slowly cooling~\cite{Wuttig2007a}.

The crystallographic switching process is accompanied by an unusually large change in the optical and electronic properties of the material, which makes PCMs important for many applications, such as optical data storage~\cite{Wuttig2007a}, non-volatile memories~\cite{Wuttig2005} and photonics~\cite{Rude2013, Rios2014}. The large optical contrast is attributed to so-called resonant bonding in the crystalline phase~\cite{Lucovsky1973, Shportko2008a}. The alignment of $p$-orbitals over next-nearest neighbors enhances the optical matrix elements, which, in turn, dramatically enhance the optical properties~\cite{Huang2010a}. The lack of medium-range $p$-orbital alignment defines the amorphous phase, which otherwise has similar local atomic arrangements and bonding. Within this framework, the effect of the phase transition on the dielectric function of the prototypical PCM, Ge$_2$Sb$_2$Te$_5$ (GST) is known. The peak in optical absorption of the crystalline state (from bonding-antibonding transitions~\cite{Shportko2008a}) induces a large real part of the dielectric function in the low-frequency limit~\cite{Huang2010a}. Upon amorphization, the peak in absorption shifts to higher energies and is reduced.  This corresponds to a reduction of the real part of the dielectric function when viewed at a single low frequency.

In equilibrium, the optical properties are linked to the structural transition. However, out of equilibrium this does not have to be the case. Recent measurements of the time-resolved optical and structural changes in the prototypical phase change material Ge$_2$Sb$_2$Te$_5$ demonstrated that the optical properties of the crystalline phase can be switched faster than structural amorphization occurs~\cite{Waldecker2015b}.

Switching the optical properties without structural motion is desirable. The lifetimes of PCM devices are limited by ionic migration and accumulated stress acquired during the structural transition. Secondly, the structural transition is inherently slow, and removing the melting/crystallization cycle could dramatically improve device speed. Therefore, the large ultrafast changes in the optical properties will be important for making high speed optical modulators~\cite{Rude2015} and other such photonic devices. Furthermore, rapid modification of optical response without switching from two stable starting points may open the possibility of novel device design.

In this paper we examine and compare, in detail, the change in optical properties of amorphous {\em and} crystalline phases of GST following excitation with femtosecond laser light when permanent switching does not occur. We deduce the influence of free photoexcited carriers and structural changes on the material's optical properties. We find that the changes observed in the amorphous phase are consistent with photo-generation of free carriers in a semiconductor, whereas the response of the crystalline state is better described by a loss of resonant bonding. Furthermore, just as the intrinsic vacancies of GST play a major role in the static optical and electrical properties~\cite{Wuttig2007b}, our results suggest that vacancies also play a significant role in determining the transient optical properties. 

\section{Static Optical Properties}
30\,nm thick samples of amorphous Ge$_2$Sb$_2$Te$_5$ (GSTa) were deposited on fused silica substrates by RF co-sputtering and capped by 10\,nm Si$_3$N$_4$. The optical and Raman spectra are shown in Figure~\ref{fig:Static}. The exact optical properties of the sample are quite sensitive to sample preparation, and the values we observe are consistent with the spread of values reported in the literature~\cite{Lee2005,Shportko2008a, Park2009}.  The GSTa Raman spectrum shows an asymmetric peak around 4.5\,THz with more weight on the high energy side. The as-deposited amorphous phase has slightly different optical and structural properties than the melt-quenched amorphous state (detailed comparison in supplementary information of ref~\onlinecite{Waldecker2015b}). The crystalline state (GSTc) can be achieved by annealing the as-deposited sample on a hot plate at 200\,$^\circ$C for 1\,h, heating at 10\,$^\circ$C/min. The phase change, in addition to drastically changing the dielectric function, also shifts the peak of the Raman/phonon spectrum to lower energies and further transfers spectral weight to the low energy side of the peak. 

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics{Static.pdf}
\caption{(color online) (a) Ellipsometry measurements of the dielectric function for the crystalline (black) and amorphous (red) phases: $\epsilon_{c/a} = \epsilon_{c/a_1} + i\epsilon_{c/a_2}$. (b) Raman measurements using 785\,nm laser. Notice the increased weight at low frequencies for the crystalline phase. Arrows correspond to phonon frequencies used in Eq.~\ref{eq:p}.\label{fig:Static}}
\end{figure}

\section{Transient Experimental Setup}
Pump probe measurements were performed in the reversible regime with 40\,fs laser pulses at a central wavelength of 800\,nm. The pump spot was focused to 230\,$\mu$m FWHM and the probe to 20\,$\mu$m FWHM to ensure that a uniformly excited sample volume was probed. The beams were measured on a CCD camera, and the fluence reported here is that obtained by the weighted average of the pump that the probe experiences. Pump and probe beams were separated by a small angle and impinged on the sample at near-normal incidence. Pump and probe were cross-polarized, and polarizers were used to filter out residual pump scatter from the detectors. No baseline subtraction was applied to the data, as baseline stability was continuously monitored for any sign of sample change. The use of thin samples on a transparent substrate allowed us to measure both changes in the reflectivity ($R$) and transmissivity ($T$), which were acquired simultaneously for each delay.

The measurements were performed at a 40\,Hz repetition rate, substantially lower than many pump-probe measurements, to ensure that the sample fully recovered between laser pulses, including dissipation of any thermal accumulation. Consequently, no changes in material properties were observed after several hours of excitation for the fluences reported here. At higher repetition rates gradual laser-induced changes to the coherent phonon spectrum of both samples were observed. The changes were consistent with the emergence of the modes of elemental Te, indicating that segregation had occurred as has been observed in other Te-based compounds~\cite{Shimada2014}.

\section{Measured Results}
The time resolved changes in $R$ and $T$ for GSTc and GSTa are shown in Figure~\ref{fig:RTgstAC} for several pump fluences well below the threshold for permanent switching of the material properties (14\,mJ\,cm$^{-2}$, ref  ~\onlinecite{Waldecker2015b}). The two phases show very different dynamics, indicative of different physical process. On short timescales, the crystalline phase shows a large increase in transmission (up to 20\%) and a smaller decrease in reflection (-4\%) . A weak coherent phonon can be observed in transmission, but is barely visible in the reflected signal. At longer times ($\approx$12\,ps), a secondary peak is observed both in transmission and more weakly in the reflection. This peak corresponds to a acoustic breathing mode of the film, and the oscillation frequency was found to be 44$\pm2$\,GHz. Given the known film thickness, we calculate the sound velocity to be 2.6\,nm/ps in GSTc, consistent with the literature~\cite{Lyeo2006}. Furthermore, the sound velocity is not found to change with increasing laser fluence, which confirms the absence of bond softening in this fluence regime. This may be clearly seen by considering the dashed line in Figure~\ref{fig:RTgstAC}a.

In contrast to GSTc, the amount of light statically reflected and transmitted both decrease in GSTa. The photo-induced fractional changes are largest in the reflected signal, which show decreases as large as 10\%. The transmission changes are smaller at 4\%. The coherent phonon signal is strongest when measured in transmission, where it dominates the signal at short times, but it is now also observable on the reflected signal.  The increased visibility of the phonon is expected, as the Raman signal of GSTa is also stronger. At longer timescales the secondary peak is no longer observed, which is a consequence of the increased damping rate and slower speed of sound for acoustic waves in the amorphous sample~\cite{Lyeo2006}. Furthermore, the dynamics observed in transmission seem more complex. The change is initially positive, before rapidly becoming negative within a few tens of femtoseconds with only small changes in the subsequent 3\,ps of evolution.

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics{TandR}
\caption{(color online) Measured changes in reflectivity and transmissivity for (a) crystalline and (b) as-deposited amorphous states of GST. The effect amplitude is linear in pump fluence. Note that no softening of the acoustic phonon (marked with dashed line) is observed in either phase.\label{fig:RTgstAC}}
\end{figure}

Although the reflectivity and transmissivity reveal many salient features of the dynamics, interpreting the results is complicated by the fact that these quantities are not fundamental material properties. Therefore, we use this data to obtain the complex dielectric function by the transfer matrix method as done previously~\cite{Waldecker2015b}. The optical properties of the Si$_3$N$_4$ layer and SiO$_2$ substrate were held constant at literature values and only the dielectric properties of the GST layer were allowed to change. We also assumed that the thickness of the GST layer did not change. As this is not strictly true due to the presence of the acoustic phonon, we limit the evaluation of the dielectric function to the first few picoseconds where the thermal expansion remains small.

The extracted time-dependent dielectric functions are shown in Figure~\ref{fig:dielectric}. In the crystalline phase, both the real ($\epsilon_1$) and imaginary ($\epsilon_2$) parts of the dielectric function show a large decrease with photoexcitation, and the coherent phonon is only observed to modulate the imaginary part. In the amorphous phase, the real part of the dielectric function decreases whereas the imaginary part increases. Furthermore, the coherent phonon is observed on both the real and imaginary terms. It is interesting to note that the complex dynamics observed in the transmission signal of GSTa (Figure~\ref{fig:RTgstAC}) are simplified when converted to the dielectric function.  Furthermore, any characterization of the rise time of the transmission signal would be shown to be erroneous upon conversion of the signal to fundamental material properties.

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics{epData}
\caption{(color online) The time-dependent dielectric function of crystalline (a) and amorphous (b) GST. In crystalline GST the optical phonon modifies only $\epsilon_2$, but modifies both terms in amorphous GST. Note the large magnitude of the effect for crystalline GST.\label{fig:dielectric}}
\end{figure}

\section{Optical Response Model}
To understand the interplay between structural and electronic degrees of freedom, we construct a phenomenological model to describe the essential dynamics of the system based on a multi-level system, schematically represented in Figure~\ref{fig:dEPgstA}a. This model is focused on the average evolution of energy through the system. The pump pulse transfers energy from the equilibrated ground state into an electronically excited state. The excited electronic population then scatters with strongly coupled optical phonons (SCOP)~\cite{Waldecker2015} or with itself~\cite{Kampfrath2005} into long lived states. These states then couple to the lattice through several possible scattering pathways. The resulting energetic configuration is one that can be described by a single (elevated) temperature. Ultimately, this hot configuration would relax back into the initial state through thermal processes.

We represent this complex behavior as a series of coupled rate equations where each level represents a unique dynamic: the pump, with temporal profile $P(t)$, excites electrons into $n_1$, represented in $I$. Energy from $I$ decays with a single time constant $\tau_1$ into $II$, capturing the average behavior of this transition. This decay captures the thermalization of electrons and optical phonons; thus population $II$ (and subsequently $III$) should not be considered purely electronic. Finally, we use time constant $\tau_2$ to represent the flow of energy from $n_2$ to the thermal population $n_3$. Due to the short temporal measurement window, we exclude thermal diffusion and cooling back to the initial state. This model gives the following coupled equations:
\begin{eqnarray*} 
	\dot{n}_1 & = & P(t) - n_1/\tau_1 \\
	\dot{n}_2 & = & n_1/\tau_1 - n_2/\tau_2 \\
	\dot{n}_3 & = & n_2/\tau_2
\end{eqnarray*}
These terms $n_i$ couple to the dielectric function through a set of complex coefficients $a_i$, which depend on the probe frequency, yielding the following expression for the electronic modification to the dielectric function:

nexttext:
where, again, the $b_i$ coefficients are complex and probe wavelength dependent. 

\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics{epfit}
\caption{(color online) Schematic represetation of the model (a). The system is electronically excited from the ground state by the pump laser (I). That energy first couples to coherent optical phonons (SCOP) (II), and later couples to the lattice at large (III). Many energy pathways (e.g. electron-electron scattering, electron-phonon scattering, grey lines) are represented with a single time constant. A representative fit using Eqs.~\ref{eq:ee} and~\ref{eq:ep} to the time-dependent dielectric function of GSTc and GSTa (b). The different fit components are also shown. The fluence was 4.6\,mJ\,cm$^{-2}$.\label{fig:dEPgstA}}
\end{figure}

The total dynamic contribution to the dielectric function is the the sum of Equations \ref{eq:ee} and \ref{eq:ep}. The sum was fit simultaneously to both the real and the imaginary part of the dielectric function, and the result was convolved with the pump pulse temporal profile to account for finite experimental time resolution. Excellent fits can be obtained at all fluences for both material phases. Example fits are shown in Figure~\ref{fig:dEPgstA}b, as well as the fit temporal evolution of all of the components.  As expected, different terms dominate at different times.

\section{Model Results}
Initially the phonon frequencies, damping rates, and the force time constant, $\tau_1$, were allowed to vary as a function of fluence; however, no significant variation was found. The averages of the fitted values were then taken, which are summarized in Table~\ref{tab:fitps}, and a second iteration was performed with these parameters held constant. The dynamics of both the amorphous and crystalline states are well described by a homogeneously broadened phonon, despite the fact that the Raman spectra shown in Figure~\ref{fig:Static}b are inhomogeneously broadened. The resulting phonon parameters are in good agreement with those observed in the static Raman spectra, marked with arrows in Figure~\ref{fig:Static}b. 

