The lifetime of electrons in $I$ is significantly dependent on the phase of the material, and scattering of these photo-excited electrons ($\tau_1$) occurs almost twice as quickly in the crystalline state as in the amorphous state.  As the electrons in $I$ are those that create a displacive force on the lattice, faster decay into $II$ translates into a shorter-lived force on the lattice.

The optical equilibration time, $\tau_2$, increases with fluence for both the amorphous and crystalline states. In the crystalline state, the value varies non-linearly from 1.6\,ps at low fluences to 2.2\, ps at 4\,mJ\,cm$^{-2}$ and is shown in more detail in Ref~\onlinecite{Waldecker2015b}. In the amorphous state the recovery is faster, ranging from 0.8\,ps at low fluences to 1.2\,ps at 4 mJ\,cm$^{-2}$. The faster recovery time of the amorphous phase is consistent with the observations of the carrier lifetime decay using THz spectroscopy~\cite{Shu2013}. 

\begin{figure*}
\includegraphics{FitResults}
\caption{Comparision of the fit results to the dielectric function. Red and black markers correspond to the real and imaginary parts of the dielectric function, respectively. Of interest more than the exact value is the comparison of polarity and linearity in pump intensity between the GSTc and GSTa. The $a_2$ and $a_3$ terms display opposite polarity real and imaginary components in GSTa, consistent with a Drude response.  However, GSTc has like-polarity response for both parts of the dielectric function. Most terms are linear in fluence, although $b_1$ and $b_2$ deviate from linearity in the crystalline phase at higher fluences. \label{fig:fitresults}}
\end{figure*}

The remaining fit parameters describe how the pump energy couples to the optical response. Their fluence dependencies are shown in Figure~\ref{fig:fitresults}. The initial photo-excited electrons ($a_1$), which produce the force that drives the phonon mode, display a near-zero-amplitude effect on the optical properties of either phase and are therefore not shown. In both phases the self-scattered electrons ($a_2$) create the majority of the electronic-driven optical changes. Both $a_2$ and $a_3$ modify the dielectric function in the crystalline phase more than in the amorphous phase. In the amorphous phase the changes to the real and imaginary terms are of opposite sign, whereas both would need to be positive to reach those of the equilibrium crystalline phase. In the crystalline phase the changes are of the same sign and decrease with increasing pump fluence, as would be expected for amorphization. The structural response of the material, the $b$ coefficients, plays a stronger role in the modulation of the dielectric function in the amorphous phase compared to the crystalline phase. Deviation from linearity in fluence of the structural coefficients is seen in the crystalline phase.

\section{Discussion}
First we consider the implications of these observations on the atomic structure. In many respects it is surprising that coherent optical phonons are observed in GSTc, as the NaCl-like structure (space group $Fm\bar 3 m$) in which only 4$a$ and 4$b$ sites are occupied~\cite{Nonaka2000} does not allow Raman-active modes. Phonons are observed because the intrinsic vacancies in GSTc break the symmetry, enabling the vibrations~\cite{Sosso2011a}. Thus, unlike most coherent phonons observed in crystalline phases, the phonon modes in both the crystalline and amorphous states of GST should be considered local modes. With this in mind, it is perhaps not surprising that the force time constant $\tau_1$ for the crystalline phase is significantly less than that of the amorphous phase. As the crystalline state is conductive, excited electronic states are delocalized. Thus electrons excited in the vicinity of the vacancies can quickly spread, reducing the time spent in the neighborhood of the vacancy, limiting the time over which the force is applied to the lattice. In the amorphous state electrons are more localized, which extends the time over which the lattice force is applied, thus inducing a large amplitude oscillation.

In addition to the force lifetime, the effect of the coherent phonons on the optical properties of both phases is markedly different. In the crystalline phase, both phonon modes modulate only the imaginary part of the dielectric function, clearly seen in the fits of the $b_1$ and $b_2$ terms in Figure~\ref{fig:fitresults}a. To the contrary, in the amorphous phase the phonon modifies both parts of the dielectric function equally ($b_1$, the 3.9\,THz phonon) or just the real part ($b_2$, the 4.5\,THz phonon). This difference is most likely due to the shift in the GSTc absorption resonance peak position shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:Static}a. Coherent phonons typically modify optical properties through band gap modulation or resonances~\cite{Papalazarou2012, Faure2013, Leuenberger2015}. In the crystalline state, the 1.5\,eV probe photon energy is very close to the absorption resonance, and thus the imaginary term likely dominates the dielectric response. The resonance shifts to significantly higher energies in the amorphous phase, so absorption plays a smaller role in the GSTa response. Consequently the changes in the real part of the dielectric function become more pronounced. Although the phonon frequency remains constant as a function of fluence, the amplitude of the phonon modes deviates from linearity in the crystalline state. This deviation is an indication of higher-order effects in the electron-phonon coupling and will be discussed in a subsequent publication~\cite{Miller2016}.

Since resonant bonding is sensitive to bond angle distortions, it has been suggested that vibrationally exciting GSTc could destabilize the lattice and laser-generated coherent phonons may be able to drive the phase transition~\cite{Kolobov2011}. Such coherent phonons would strongly modulate the {\em real} part of the dielectric function, which is sensitive to resonant bonding. This is not observed. The lack of observation may be because observable phonons represent local atomic motion near vacancies and thus may not influence the angles of the more spatially distributed resonant bonds. Furthermore, in the range of excitation measured here, up to approximately 50\% of single shot fluence for both states, both the coherent acoustic and optical phonons show no indication of softening. This shows that the lattice potential is not significantly modified in either phase. This is in contrast with other measurements in which a softening has been observed~\cite{Hernandez-Rueda2011a}. We believe that the reason for this difference is that the low repetition rate used in our measurements intentionally limits DC heating.

We now consider the electronically driven changes to the dielectric function. In both phases, the carriers that generate the phonon force, $a_1$, have little or no effect on the optical properties of GST, and the dominant term is $a_2$. The optical response from photoexcited electrons is often considered a change in the Drude response of the material~\cite{Huang1998, Kim2002, Sundaram2002}. Such a response can be easily estimated. We estimate the size of the expected Drude response by using the values of the scattering time and conductivity of GSTc reported in ref~\onlinecite{Mendoza-Galvan2000} and use the same scattering time for GSTa. Assuming that photoexciation creates 30\% of the equilibrium number of charges, we obtain
\begin{eqnarray*}
    \Delta\epsilon_\mathrm{Drude,amorph} = -0.3 + 0.04i \\
    \Delta\epsilon_\mathrm{Drude,crystal} = -2.3 + 0.30i
\end{eqnarray*}
Although a 30\% excitation is likely large, it demonstrates that the changes observed in the amorphous phase are consistent with an increase in the carrier density.  Note that the observed response matches both magnitude and sign for both terms of the dielectric function, as also observed in GeSb ~\cite{Callan2001}. More striking is that the observed response of the imaginary term in GSTc is the wrong sign, and thus this response is unlikely to be due to the Drude response. 

Instead we ascribe the GSTc electronic response to resonant bonding behavior. Resonant bonding can be altered two ways: by changing the charge distribution (since resonant bonds are at the top of the valence band~\cite{Huang2010a}) or by changing the extended crystallographic bond angle order. As we observe dielectric function changes on the femtosecond timescale - faster than the excitation is transferred to the lattice ($\tau_2=1.6\,ps$) - we believe an altered charge distribution modifies the transfer matrix elements due to population filling and alters the dielectric function. In this picture, some of the distributed electrons in the resonant bonding states are photoexcited, changing the material optical properties. As this energy is transferred to the lattice, this state of diminished resonant bonding will continue because of the thermal disorder of the bond angles over extended distances. The thermal energy must dissipate before resonant bonds can be re-established. However, we stress that these bond angle changes are not induced by the coherent Raman-active phonon modes and are instead due to the thermal distribution of all modes, acoustic and optical.

\section{Conclusions}
In this work we have addressed the photoinduced changes in the dielectric function of both the amorphous and crystalline phases of GST. We find that the response at 800\,nm is sensitive to both structural and electronic effects. Although the measured time dynamics of the reflectivity and transmission look qualitatively different in the two samples, conversion to the dielectric function reveals that the underlying dynamics are similar. 

In both cases, the response is dominated by photo-excited electrons. In GSTa the electrons respond in a Drude manner and are scattered quickly. In GSTc the photoexcited electrons change the charge distribution, altering the optical matrix elements that stem from resonant bonding, and take longer to recover. 

In addition to the electronic response we also obtain insights into the behavior of the lattice. We observe both coherent acoustic and optical phonon modes. In the range of fluences measured here, we do not see any change in the frequencies of these oscillations, which suggests that the lattice potential and bonding are relatively unaffected by photoexcitation at levels up to 50\% of the single-shot transformation fluence. We argue that the coherent optical phonons primarily modulate the bonding-antibonding transition, and that, as these modes are localized near vacancies, they do not significantly perturb resonant bonding in the crystalline state. Furthermore these local modes can be more easily excited in the amorphous state due to the greater presence of defects that is a natural consequence of the increased crystallographic disorder.

Practically, the relative changes in both the amorphous and crystalline state are of a similar amplitude. Thus the state of choice will depend on whether large changes in transmission or reflection are required. However, the excited electrons persist longer in the crystalline state. As lattice heating drives the permanent phase transition, the crystalline phase may present better opportunities for extracting energy from the electronic system before it is transferred to the lattice, enabling larger transient changes to be induced without permanent structural modifications being induced. 

